European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Maybe it's due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that has been a crossroads of Europe's intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations for centuries.
Perhaps all these factors combined have led me to the conviction that Europe is a single political entity, the security of which is indivisible.
The idea that there could be two Europas forever – one democratic, stable, wealthy, and integrated, and one less democratic, less stable, less wealthy, and isolated – is an illusion.
It's like a part of a room could be heated while the other part remains cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Each significant event echoes across Europe.
If Europe is to become one, if the European Union is to take in the new post-communist democracies – which is in the interest of Europe –, a series of essential tasks must be tackled, both within the new democracies as well as in the European and Atlantic community.
Firstly, Europe must promote community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a living society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies to become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse and interconnected European civil society structures become, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer various solidarity tasks to self-administered institutions and non-profit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economic it will be; and the better it will satisfy those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to people or their associations.
Authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest basis for those forms of solidarity that can only be exercised by states.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the policy of appeasement with its renunciation of European solidarity, which led to the capitulation of Munich.
This experience is still a powerful call to vigilance.
The evil must be countered as soon as it appears; however, it is not enough if only governments act.
Because government policy grows out of the feelings of civil society, out of the people.
Worry about security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should be characterized by an ability to quickly decide and quickly implement communal decisions – reforms that recent developments in Yugoslavia have shown to be necessary.
The intervention of NATO last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom as well as the interests of overall European security require interventions outside the EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better it is.
Unfortunately, there may be situations in which the UN mandate may not come, although an intervention would be in the interest of many people, all of Europe, and even human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
However, further measures are still required in the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of the expanded European civil society.
Ten thousand human lives and an enormous amount of material could have been saved in Kosovo, in Bosnia and Herzegovina, and in other parts of the former Yugoslavia, if the international community had taken action at the beginning of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, one only acted with timidity.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be watching the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot be dependent on the US forever, especially not with regard to European problems.
It must be able to agree on its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can exist as a respected part of the world order if it proves itself to be incapable of agreeing on means and ways to protect human rights, not only on its territory, but also in areas that may join it one day.
Such an EU expansion is only conceivable if it advances hand in hand with a courageous reform of EU institutions.
I am hopeful that the government conference on institutional reform will submit practical proposals for the progress of the Union.
However, I consider this as the beginning of a process that may take decades and should be guided by a lasting effort to accelerate and make the EU decision-making process more transparent.
One point related to institutional reform is the question of how one can give smaller states the certainty that they will not be simply outvoted by the larger ones, while still taking due account of the size of individual states.
A possible solution is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber are not elected directly but are elected by the parliaments of member states from their own ranks.
The first chamber of the EU - i.e., the current parliament - would thus reflect the size of individual member states, while the second chamber would increase equality, with the same number of representatives for each state.
Eventually, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution - a text that all European children could learn.
A constitution of this kind requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and obligations of both European citizens and states, the underlying values, and the significance and goals of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their principal powers, and their relationships with each other.
Such a basic law would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal supranational state feared by euroskeptics.
It would, however, help citizens in an integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, understand it better, see the importance of the EU for their lives, and, as a consequence, identify with it.
